publish:property.name: Name
publish:property.publish:value: Figure RS.02 - Resource Function Spec relationship

ownedComment.body:
A ResourceFunctionSpec specifies a function as a behaviour to transform inputs of any nature into outputs of any nature independently from the way it is provided. It is typically created by a function designer who may not have specific knowledge on realisation architecture (for example using English text explanations with diagrams, like RFC standards, or preferably a machine interpretable language). The realisation of a ResourceFunctionSpec may be achieved by different ways; either SoftwareSpecification, PhysicalBlackBoxSpec or SoftBlackBoxSpecification. Examples: manually or automated by software or hardware implementing algorithms etc… without any impact on the definition of the functions itself.
A SoftwareSpecification specifies properties or associated information that characterizes a software, such as: - the release number, the status of the release, license conditions... - hosting platform requirements such as OS, disk and memory space... - input and output configuration and requirements - and includes all files required for deployment and installation such as installation manager SoftBlackBoxSpec is a box with embedded software in it and PhysicalBlackBoxSpec is a box with any other internal mechanism realizing the function. A SoftConnectionPointSpec, resp. an ElectronicConnectionPointSpec are realisation of Connection Points either as software Programming Interfaces (API) or as Electronic interface (signal processing).
HostingPlatformRequirementsSpec is used to represent the common characteristics and associations of resources in the infrastructure (e.g. compute, storage, network). The derived association /SoftwareSpecificatonRequires is used to document the requirements necessary to a platform to be capable of hosting the concerned software before it is installed.
A SofwareSupportPackage represents the package acquired by a consumer from a software vendor. It can be materialized as one or several files (data) downloaded online or copied on a physical support. It contains all files required for deployment and installation such as installation manager and at minimum, one of the files constitutes the set of machine readable instructions that will be executed automatically after it is installed.
An InstalledSoftware consists of encoded information or computer instructions deployed on a machine such that it can be executed. An InstalledSoftware is a SoftwareSpecification deployed using the SoftwareSupportPackage and HostingPlatformRequirements. Each InstalledSoftware specifies their input and output respectively with SoftConnectionPoints. Note: the Software entity has been renamed InstalledSoftware in SID 17.0.

publish:property.name: Name
publish:property.publish:value: Figure RS.03 - Resource Function Spec inheritance

ownedComment.body:
The ResourceFunction / ResourceFunctionSpec concept is very broad and can be applied to many different domains.
NetworkFunction / NetworkFunctionSpec would correspond to the description of the behaviour of a function running in the network domain. Instances of such artefacts can be specific functions for a given layer (RouterFunction, SwichingFunction, GatewayFunction…). OfficeFunction / OfficeFunctionSpec and GameFunction / GameFunctionSpec would be respective specialisation in the Office domain and Game domain. Another example could be MeteoFunction / MeteoFunctionSpec in the Meteo domain, consisting of describing how meteo data (pressure , temperature, wind) would be transformed to create meteo reports. Instances of such MeteoFunction / MeteoFunctionSpec artefacts would be specifically created for different kinds of meteo reports: national, regional, local, mountain, see, storm, etc…).
HostingPlatformRequirementsSpec is used to represent the common characteristics and associations of resources in the infrastructure. Compute, Storage and Network are examples of requirements for SoftwareSpecifications.

ownedComment.body:
A ResourceFunctionSpec specifies a function as a behaviour to transform inputs of any nature into outputs of any nature independently from the way it is provided. It is typically created by a function designer who may not have specific knowledge on realisation architecture (for example using English text explanations with diagrams, like RFC standards, or preferably a machine interpretable language). The realisation of a ResourceFunctionSpec may be achieved by different ways; either SoftwareSpecification, PhysicalBlackBoxSpec or SoftBlackBoxSpecification.
But we also need to define at a ProductSpec, CFSSpec and RFSSpec level the ResourceFunctions covered by them. It can be useful when you define a ProductSpecification you want to propose before knowing the technical solution you are going to use. At the end, before proposing a ProductSpecification you must be sure that all the ResourceFunctionSpec requested by the ProductSpecification are covered by its technical solution (RFSSpec) thanks to its ResourceSpecification. Note: SoftwareSpecification, PhysicalBlackBoxSpec and SoftBlackBoxSpecification are sub-classes from ResourceSpecification.

publish:property.name: Description
publish:property.publish:value: The ResourceCapacityDemand represents the amount of ResourceCapacity that is required, planned to be consumed or has been consumed....

ownedComment.body:
The ResourceCapacityDemand represents the amount of ResourceCapacity that is required, planned to be consumed or has been consumed.
The HostingPlatformRequirementsSpec is used to represent the common characteristics and associations of resources in the infrastructure (e.g. compute, storage, network) for a SoftwareSpecification. The HostingPlatformRequirementsSpec requires a ResourceCapacityDemand that in this case specifies the amounts (minimum, maximum...) of capacity required.
A HostingPlatformRequirement implements a HostingPlatformRequirementSpec for a specific InstalledSoftware. It requires a ResourceCapacityDemand that in this case specifies the amounts (minimum, maximum...) of capacity planned or consumed. Refer to Capacity guide book for more explanation about the Capacity model.
